from hydrothermal systems and as a reagent/byproduct linked to the proline network. This connection step is added only to integrate the environmental flow and does not replace any Patel et al. (2015) proline step; NH3 participation in the network and environmental abundance are explicitly discussed in the review, while the hydrothermal source assignment is a conservative geochemical connector."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal reduced C1 production to formaldehyde-equivalent feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing vent setting; represents hydrothermal delivery of reduced carbon into surface aldehyde chemistry"}, "mechanism": "CO2 hydrogenation on iron minerals yields reduced one-carbon organics represented here by formaldehyde-equivalent feedstock usable in downstream surface aldehyde chemistry.", "reasoning": "The review notes that simple feedstock aldehydes can be supplied from hydrothermal environments to surface pools. This connector is consistent with established hydrothermal reduced-carbon chemistry and is included only to connect the literature-grounded proline route to a hydrothermal source pool. The direct proline pathway remains that of Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface photochemical generation and concentration of hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated evaporitic/geothermal pool; represents atmospheric/photochemical HCN input concentrated at surface"}, "mechanism": "Surface photochemistry and evaporative concentration provide HCN as a cyanosulfidic carbon-nitrogen feedstock.", "reasoning": "The review explicitly identifies HCN as a prebiotically abundant upstream hub from atmospheric photochemistry, volcanic outgassing, and impact chemistry and places the proline route in surface cyanosulfidic settings. This reaction is a network connector for source availability and does not alter the Patel et al. (2015) proline sequence."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface formation/availability of acrolein from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal surface pool, evaporative concentration; represented as aldehyde-condensation/thermal transformation route"}, "mechanism": "Reduced carbon feedstocks undergo surface photochemical/thermal transformation to unsaturated aldehydes represented by acrolein, a plausible precursor to 3-aminopropanal.", "reasoning": "The review states that 3-aminopropanal can form prebiotically from acrolein plus NH3 and notes acrolein can arise from formaldehyde condensation or thermal decomposition of glycerol. This connector respects the literature by using acrolein only as an upstream precursor to the established Patel et al. (2015) route."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface production of 3-aminopropanal from acrolein and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pool; Michael-type ammonia addition to acrolein or equivalent amino-aldehyde generating chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to acrolein to furnish the C3 amino aldehyde 3-aminopropanal, the immediate entry point to the experimentally demonstrated proline route.", "reasoning": "The literature review explicitly identifies 3-aminopropanal as forming prebiotically from acrolein + NH3 or related cyanosulfidic chemistry, while also noting its uncertain stability as an open question. This reaction is therefore a justified connecting step to the Patel et al. (2015) route and addresses the documented feedstock gap."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from 3-aminopropanal and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration on sulfide/clay surfaces under cyanosulfidic conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool, cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Strecker-type nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal forms the cyanohydrin aminonitrile 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "Directly follows the experimentally demonstrated Step 1 of the proline pathway in Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015). The review specifies aqueous, ambient surface cyanosulfidic conditions. Mineral agents are included here to satisfy network-format requirements for surface reactions, serving as plausible concentrating/mineral-support phases consistent with the same surface setting; the core chemistry and conditions remain those of Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Thiolation-cyclization to 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "H2S-rich cyanosulfidic medium on sulfide/clay mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2S atmosphere, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "H2S attacks the nitrile carbon to generate a thioamide; the terminal amine then cyclizes intramolecularly onto the thioamide carbon to form the five-membered pyrrolidine ring with NH3 release.", "reasoning": "Directly follows Step 2 reported by Patel et al. (2015), exactly as summarized in the literature review: aqueous, ambient, H2S-mediated thiolation-cyclization in surface cyanosulfidic conditions. The explicit sulfur-cycle role of H2S is central to the reported mechanism."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu0) with H2S", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu/H2S-mediated reductive cleavage of the C-OH functionality removes the hydroxyl group from the cyclic thione, giving pyrrolidine-2-thione and water.", "reasoning": "Directly follows Step 3 in Patel et al. (2015): reductive deoxygenation under aqueous ambient surface conditions using elemental copper and H2S. The review specifically highlights Cu0 availability as plausible but uncertain, and identifies this as a key challenge in the pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Thione-to-nitrile exchange to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "HCN-rich cyanosulfidic medium on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN present, sulfur recycling"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide attacks the thioamide carbon of pyrrolidine-2-thione, replacing sulfur with a nitrile and releasing H2S, thereby recycling sulfur back into the network.", "reasoning": "Directly follows Step 4 of Patel et al. (2015), under aqueous ambient cyanosulfidic conditions with HCN present. The review explicitly emphasizes H2S recycling in this step as a hallmark of the sulfur cycle in the pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "two equivalents of water consumed overall; nitrile hydrolysis may be kinetically slow"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydrolysis via amide intermediate converts the ring nitrile to the carboxylic acid, releasing ammonia and furnishing L-proline.", "reasoning": "Directly follows Step 5 of Patel et al. (2015): aqueous ambient nitrile hydrolysis to proline. The review notes this as a potential kinetic bottleneck under realistic prebiotic conditions, which is acknowledged here."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical wet-dry condensation of proline to proline-containing dipeptide", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay mineral interface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling in prebiotic pools; represented as self-condensation of two proline equivalents"}, "mechanism": "Repeated dehydration-rehydration on mineral interfaces promotes peptide bond formation between two proline molecules, producing a proline-containing dipeptide.", "reasoning":