hemistry and vent nitrogen/sulfur cycling literature; proline pathway dependence on H2S and NH3 follows Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface generation of acrolein-like C3 aldehyde from reduced C1 feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2, borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic/geothermal pool; condensative carbonyl chemistry; connective step to literature-noted acrolein precursor"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and condensative carbonyl chemistry converts reduced C1 feedstock into a reactive C3 unsaturated aldehyde pool represented by acrolein.", "reasoning": "The literature review states that 3-aminopropanal can arise from acrolein plus ammonia, and acrolein may derive from formaldehyde condensation or glycerol decomposition. Because Patel et al. (2015) focuses on the downstream proline route rather than a definitive acrolein synthesis, this step is explicitly marked as a necessary but speculative connective bridge, included only to supply the literature-noted precursor class without altering the validated proline sequence (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface formation of 3-aminopropanal from acrolein and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ambient cyanosulfidic/geothermal pool; Michael-type ammonia addition to acrolein; precursor provisioning"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to the beta-carbon of acrolein, followed by proton transfers to furnish 3-aminopropanal.", "reasoning": "The curated review explicitly identifies 3-aminopropanal as plausibly forming prebiotically from acrolein plus NH3, although this upstream step was not the central experimentally demonstrated focus of Patel et al. (2015). Accordingly this reaction is included as a literature-consistent precursor supply step, while the target-forming steps remain exactly those demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from 3-aminopropanal", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient temperature", "pressure": "ambient pressure", "catalyst": "surface cyanosulfidic mineral context", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool; HCN-rich cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation by nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal, preserving the terminal amine.", "reasoning": "This is Reaction R1 of the experimentally demonstrated proline pathway: 3-aminopropanal + HCN gives 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile under aqueous ambient surface conditions (Patel et al., 2015). Mineral agents are specified here to satisfy network formatting requirements for surface reactions, but the literature-supported core chemistry and conditions are those of Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Thiolation-cyclization to 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient temperature", "pressure": "ambient pressure", "catalyst": "H2S-driven cyanosulfidic cyclization in surface pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2S atmosphere; cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "H2S converts the nitrile to a thioamide equivalent, then the pendant amine attacks intramolecularly to form the five-membered pyrrolidine ring with NH3 release.", "reasoning": "This is Reaction R2 of the Patel et al. (2015) pathway. It is the key ring-closing step that creates the pyrrolidine scaffold unique to proline, consuming H2S and releasing NH3. The reaction and conditions follow Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient temperature", "pressure": "ambient pressure", "catalyst": "Cu0 with H2S", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic reducing system; ambient aqueous conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu/H2S-mediated reductive deoxygenation removes the C3 hydroxyl group from the cyclic thione, yielding pyrrolidine-2-thione and water.", "reasoning": "This is Reaction R3 of Patel et al. (2015), specifically requiring elemental copper and H2S as the reducing system. The step is experimentally documented and is essential for obtaining the fully reduced pyrrolidine-2-thione intermediate. Patel et al. (2015) is the direct source."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Thione-to-nitrile exchange", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient temperature", "pressure": "ambient pressure", "catalyst": "HCN-driven thione-to-nitrile exchange in cyanosulfidic pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN present; sulfur recycling"}, "mechanism": "HCN attacks the thioamide carbon, replacing the thione sulfur with a nitrile function and releasing H2S.", "reasoning": "This is Reaction R4 of Patel et al. (2015). It converts the sulfur-containing cyclic intermediate into pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile and regenerates H2S, creating the sulfur-recycling convergence emphasized in the literatu