s lies in the unsupported generation of H2S/NH3 from water and the weakly justified formaldehyde-to-acrolein progression.', \"The path to proline is solid once 3-aminopropanal is available, but the proposed precursor provisioning through formaldehyde-to-acrolein is the weak link. This mirrors one of the literature's stated open questions: reliable prebiotic access to 3-aminopropanal.\", 'The surface-to-biochemical transition is conceptually appropriate, but the biochemical condensation step is stoichiometrically flawed as written. A Pro-Pro dipeptide cannot form from a single proline molecule; two proline equivalents are required, and one water is released. This weakens the downstream utilization claim though not the proline synthesis itself.', 'This pathway best demonstrates environmental interconnection in a graph sense, but not in a chemically robust way. The hydrothermal-to-surface handoff is weakened by implausible feeder chemistry, so the end-to-end route is less convincing than the pure literature core.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network is centered on the experimentally demonstrated 5-step surface cyanosulfidic route of Patel et al. (2015) from 3-aminopropanal to proline, using HCN and H2S as recycled hub reagents and the documented Cu/H2S reduction for deoxygenation. To satisfy whole-network connectivity without inventing contradictory chemistry, hydrothermal nodes are limited to plausible provisioning and transport of simple feedstocks explicitly identified in the literature review as prebiotically available from hydrothermal/volcanic systems (HCN, H2S, NH3, H2O). Biochemical nodes use the literature-supported role of proline entering the amino-acid pool and participating in peptide formation, with corrected stoichiometry. Because the literature supports one validated synthesis route to proline and warns against unsupported alternatives, the 10 pathways below are distinct route variants through the same connected network, differing by feeder provenance, sulfur recycling, and downstream biochemical incorporation rather than by invented target-forming chemistry.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"Cu\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"copper\",\n      \"common_name\": \"elemental copper\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/Cu\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H16N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidin-2-ylcarbonylproline\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pro-Pro dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal provisioning and transport of hydrogen sulfide to surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal sulfur-rich fluids; transport to surface by venting/outgassing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Geochemical sulfur mobilization and vent delivery rather than a single stoichiometric laboratory synthesis step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review identifies H2S as prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing and hydrothermal vents and as a required reagent in the proline pathway. This node is included only to represent hydrothermal-to-surface feedstock supply and environmental interconnection, not to claim a new target-forming route. Mineral sulfide context is consistent with iron-sulfur hydrothermal settings, while the proline-forming use of H2S follows Patel et al. (2015). This provisioning step is therefore connective and partially speculative, added only because the network requires Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface linkage and the review explicitly states hydrothermal delivery of simple feedstocks.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal provisioning and transport of ammonia to surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent fluids; represented as availability/transport of NH3 rather than strict net synthesis from water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Availability and transport of reduced nitrogen in hydrothermal fluids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review identifies NH3 as prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing, atmospheric photochemistry, and hydrothermal systems and notes that 3-aminopropanal can arise from ammonia addition chemistry upstream of the validated proline route. This reaction is deliberately framed as provisioning/transport rather than an unsupported stoichiometric generation from water, addressing prior feedback. Connection to the target network is justified by Patel et al. (2015) and by the review's environmental-interconnection section; specific mineral context is included to satisfy hydrothermal agent requirements.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal/volcanic provisioning and transport of hydrogen cyanide to surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"represented as geochemical delivery of HCN-compatible reduced carbon/nitrogen species to surface pools; no claim of exact stoichiometric vent synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Environmental feedstock supply into surface cyanosulfidic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review treats HCN as a prebiotically abundant upstream hub generated by atmospheric photochemistry, volcanic activity, and impact processes, and states that simple feedstocks can be supplied from hydrothermal environments to surface pools. To avoid contradicting the literature by inventing a target-specific alternative chemistry, this node functions only as a transport/provisioning connector for the network. The actual proline-forming uses of HCN are exactly those demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formation/availability of 3-aminopropanal from cyanosulfidic feedstock pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite), TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic surface setting; this node represents formation/maintenance of 3-aminopropanal within the surface feedstock network rather than a single validated elementary step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensed representation of the literature-noted upstream generation of 3-aminopropanal from simple surface feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) experimentally validated the downstream 5-step proline sequence beginning with 3-aminopropanal. The review explicitly notes that 3-aminopropanal can arise in cyanosulfidic/surface chemistry and discusses its uncertain availability as an open question. This connective step is therefore marked as speculative but necessary to embed the validated route in a connected whole-network without inventing an alternative proline synthesis. Surface mineral agents are included to satisfy schema requirements and to reflect cyanosulfidic surface settings discussed in the review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from 3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface cyanosulfidic mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools; ambient temperature and pressure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation by nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Reaction R1 of the literature review and is directly supported by Patel et al. (2015). The exact substrate-product relation, ambient aqueous surface setting, and cyanosulfidic context follow the reported pathway. Mineral agents here denote the required surface mineral context of the evaporitic/cyanosulfidic environment and do not replace the literature mechanism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Thiolation-cyclization to 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"H2S-rich cyanosulfidic surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous, H2S atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2S attacks the nitrile to form a thioamide, followed by intramolecular amine attack and five-membered ring closure with NH3 release.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Reaction R2 of the literature review and follows Patel et al. (2015) exactly in substrate/product logic, aqueous ambient surface conditions, and mechanistic interpretation. The review emphasizes that this step simultaneously accomplishes thiolation and cyclization to the pyrrolidine ring. Surface mineral agents are included to satisfy the required schema while preserving the literature chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Cu/H2S reducing system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated reductive removal of the C3 hydroxyl group with loss of water to give the reduced thione.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Reaction R3 of the literature review and is directly supported by Patel et al. (2015). The review specifically documents elemental copper and H2S as the reductive system and notes copper's prebiotic plausibility in sulfidic surface settings. This step is a key bottleneck and the literature flags copper availability as an open question; the network retains the documented chemistry without modification.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Thione-to-nitrile exchange\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface cyanosulfidic mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous, HCN present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide attacks the thioamide carbon of pyrrolidine-2-thione, replacing sulfur and releasing H2S to form the nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Reaction R4 of the literature review and follows Patel et al. (2015) directly. The review highlights this as a hallmark sulfur-to-nitrogen interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry and notes that H2S is regenerated here, creating a sulfur-recycling convergence with the previous cyclization step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface aqueous mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous, ambient temperature; shorthand for sequential hydrolysis consuming two water equivalents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydrolysis via the amide to the carboxylic acid with ammonia release.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Reaction R5 of the literature review and is directly supported by Patel et al. (2015). The review notes that this step may be kinetically slow at ambient temperature, making it a plausible late-stage bottleneck. The node is retained exactly as the documented target-forming step, with the caveat from the review that the demonstrated pathway yields racemic proline; the target label follows user request, but the underlying chemistry is literature-based.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical incorporation of proline into dipeptides\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces or in prebiotic pools; dehydration condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of two proline molecules to a dipeptide with release of one water molecule.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review states that proline produced by the surface cyanosulfidic route enters the prebiotic amino-acid pool and can participate in peptide formation under biochemical wet-dry cycling. This reaction is included to represent downstream utilization and environmental interconnection and corrects the stoichiometric error flagged in prior attempts by using two proline equivalents and one water product. The downstream role is consistent with Patel et al. (2015) and with the review's biochemical discussion, although this specific dipeptide product is a generic prebiotic incorporation step rather than part of the experimentally demonstrated proline synthesis sequence.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic proline synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct literature-validated surface route from 3-aminopropanal to proline through aminonitrile, thione, nitrile, and hydrolysis intermediates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN-fed surface cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal/volcanic provisioning of HCN feeds the validated surface sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal H2S-fed surface cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal sulfur supply feeds the thiolation and Cu/H2S reduction steps of the validated surface pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal NH3-supported 3-aminopropanal provisioning route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal ammonia contributes to the uncertain but literature-noted surface availability of 3-aminopropanal before entry into the validated proline pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Fully connected Hydrothermal to Surface proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"All hydrothermal feedstock provisioning nodes connect into the literature-validated surface synthesis without altering the core chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfur-recycling proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pathway emphasizing that H2S consumed during thiolation-cyclization is regenerated during thione-to-nitrile exchange.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile hub route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pathway emphasizing 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile as the branch-point aminonitrile hub leading into ring closure and proline formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclic thione hub route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pathway emphasizing pyrrolidine-2-thione as the central cyclic hub between ring construction and nitrile installation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Penultimate nitrile hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pathway emphasizing pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the final common intermediate converging to proline by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface to Biochemical incorporation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Validated surface synthesis of proline followed by corrected stoichiometric incorporation into a proline-containing dipeptide in the biochemical environment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "The network is centered on the experimentally demonstrated 5-step surface cyanosulfidic route of Patel et al. (2015) from 3-aminopropanal to proline, using HCN and H2S as recycled hub reagents and the documented Cu/H2S reduction for deoxygenation. To satisfy whole-network connectivity without inventing contradictory chemistry, hydrothermal nodes are limited to plausible provisioning and transport of simple feedstocks explicitly identified in the literature review as prebiotically available from hydrothermal/volcanic systems (HCN, H2S, NH3, H2O). Biochemical nodes use the literature-supported role of proline entering the amino-acid pool and participating in peptide formation, with corrected stoichiometry. Because the literature supports one validated synthesis route to proline and warns against unsupported alternatives, the 10 pathways below are distinct route variants through the same connected network, differing by feeder provenance, sulfur recycling, and downstream biochemical incorporation rather than by invented target-forming chemistry.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/