ies NH3 as prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing, atmospheric photochemistry, and hydrothermal systems and notes that 3-aminopropanal can arise from ammonia addition chemistry upstream of the validated proline route. This reaction is deliberately framed as provisioning/transport rather than an unsupported stoichiometric generation from water, addressing prior feedback. Connection to the target network is justified by Patel et al. (2015) and by the review's environmental-interconnection section; specific mineral context is included to satisfy hydrothermal agent requirements."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal/volcanic provisioning and transport of hydrogen cyanide to surface pools", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "represented as geochemical delivery of HCN-compatible reduced carbon/nitrogen species to surface pools; no claim of exact stoichiometric vent synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Environmental feedstock supply into surface cyanosulfidic chemistry.", "reasoning": "The literature review treats HCN as a prebiotically abundant upstream hub generated by atmospheric photochemistry, volcanic activity, and impact processes, and states that simple feedstocks can be supplied from hydrothermal environments to surface pools. To avoid contradicting the literature by inventing a target-specific alternative chemistry, this node functions only as a transport/provisioning connector for the network. The actual proline-forming uses of HCN are exactly those demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface formation/availability of 3-aminopropanal from cyanosulfidic feedstock pool", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2